              <tr class='athing comtr ' id='16526789'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16526789' href='vote?id=16526789&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525735'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=nine_k" class="hnuser">nine_k</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16526789">6 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16526789"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="3" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16526789)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">The v8 engine behind Atom is an incredibly efficient compiler,  a just-in-time compiler. Without it, all current JS interfaces would be comically slow.<p>The problem with JS is that its execution model is built around highly dynamic features that are hard to compile efficiently. It also lacks a nice type system, though Typescript helps a lot.<p>The problem with Atom performance, <i>I suspect</i>, is mostly with its using a web browser <i>and DOM</i> to exit text. I bet that elisp is seriously slower than JS on v8, but Emacs is faster than Atom, because its presentation layer is more efficient (while less capable).<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16526789&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525735%2316526789">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
      </table></td></tr>
