            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16525997' href='vote?id=16525997&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525735'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=moosingin3space" class="hnuser">moosingin3space</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16525997">10 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16525997"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="20" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16525997)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">Every text editor beyond the most basic is incredibly complex. Terminals are a complete mess, so every terminal-based text editor certainly can&#x27;t be called &quot;simple&quot;, and that&#x27;s not even beginning to consider extensibility! Emacs and Vim have entire interpreters embedded into their codebases, for instance.<p>Maybe text editors with an extensible feature set really are more complex than we&#x27;ve been led to believe?<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16525997&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16525735%2316525997">reply</a></u>
